  content obj_root_law_sections_3_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_3_footnotes
  sourcePage 3
obj_root_law_sections_3_content:
  string
  line 3
  line `( B ) which is not for the time being registered in any country but in t he case of which either`
  line `the operator of the aircraft or each person entitled as owner to any legal or beneficial interest in it`
  line `satisfies the f ollowing requirements, namely: —`
  line `( i ) that he is a person qualified to be owner of a legal or beneficial interest in an aircraft`
  line `registered in India; and`
  line `( ii ) that he resides or has his principal place of business in India; or`
  line `( C ) Which, for the time being registered in any country other than Indi a, is for the time being`
  line `chartered by demise to a person who, or to persons each of who m, satisfies the requirements`
  line `specified in sub - clause ( B ) ( i ) and ( ii );`
  line `( f ) “ military aircraft ” means an aircraft of the naval, military or air force of any country and`
  line `includes every aircraft, commanded by a person in naval, military or air force service, detailed for the`
  line purpose;
  line `( g ) “ operator ”, in relation to an aircraft at any time, means the pe rson who at that time has the`
  line `management of the aircraft;`
  line `( h ) “ pilot in command ”, in relation to an aircraft, means a person who for the time being is in`
  line `charge of the piloting of the aircraft without being under the direction of any other pilot in the air craft`
  line `and responsible for the operation and safety of the aircraft during f l ight time;`
  line `( i ) “ Tokyo C onvention ” means the Convention on offences and certain other acts committed on`
  line `board aircraft signed at Tokyo on the Fourteenth day of September, 1963;`
  line `( j ) any reference to a country or to the territorial limits thereof shall be construed as including a`
  line `reference to the territorial waters, if any, of that country, and any reference to an aircraft in flight shall`
  line `include a reference to an aircraft during any p eriod when it is on the surface of the sea or land but not`
  line `within the territorial limits of any country.`
  line `( 2 ) For the purposes of this Act, the period during which an aircraft is in flight shall be deemed to`
  line `include any period from the moment when power is applied for the purpose of the aircraft taking off on a`
  line `flight until the moment when the landing run, if any, at the termination of that flight ends; and for the`
  line `purpose of section 5 the aforesaid period shall also be deemed to include —`
  line `( i ) any further period from the moment when all external doors, if any, of the aircraft are closed`
  line `following embarkation for a flight until the moment when any such door is opened for`
  line `disembarkation, after that flight;`
  line `( ii ) if the aircraft makes a forced landing, any peri od thereafter until the time —`
  line `( a ) in a case where the forced landing takes place in India, when the appropriate authority`
  line `arrives at the place of such forced landing; and`
  line `( b ) in any other case, when the appropriate authority takes over the responsibility f or the`
  line `aircraft and for the persons and property on board the aircraft.`
  line `CHAPTER III`
  line `O FFENCES`
  line `3. Application of criminal law to aircraft. — ( 1 ) Any act or omission taking place on board an`
  line `Indian registered aircraft while in flight elsewhere than in or over India which, if taking place in India,`
  line `would constitute an offence under any law in force in Indi a shall constitute that offence:`
  line `Provided that this sub - section shall not apply to any act or omission which is expressly or impliedly`
  line `authorised by or under a ny law of a country outside India, where the aircraft is in flight.`
  line `( 2 ) No proceedings for an offence under any law in force in India, committed on board an aircraft`
  line `while in flight elsewhere than in or over India (other than an offence under the Aircraft`
  line `Act, 1934 [ 22 of 1934 ] ) shall be instituted except by or with the consent of the Central Government.`
obj_root_law_sections_3_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_4:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-4
  sectionNo (4)
  orderNo 4
  title `Page 4`
  content obj_root_law_sections_4_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_4_footnotes
  sourcePage 4
obj_root_law_sections_4_content:
  string
  line 4
  line `( 3 ) Nothing contained in sub - section ( 2 ) shall prevent the arrest, or the issue of a warrant for the`
  line `arrest, of any person in resp ect of any offence, or the remanding in custody or o n bail of any person`
  line `charged with any offence.`
  line `4. Provisions as to Extradition Act. — For the purposes of application of the Extradition`
  line `Act, 1962 (34 of 1962), to crimes committed on board an aircraft in flight, any aircraft registered in a`
  line `Convention country shall, at any time while that aircraft is in flight, be deemed to be within the`
  line `jurisdiction of that country, whether or not it is for the time being also within the jurisdiction of any o ther`
  line country.
  line `5. Powers of commander of aircraft. — ( 1 ) If the commander of an aircraft in flight, wherever the`
  line `aircraft may be, has reasonable grounds to believe in respect of an y person on board the aircraft —`
  line `( a ) that the person in question has done or is about to do any act on the aircraft while it is in flight`
  line `which jeopardises or may jeopardise —`
  line `( i ) the safety of the aircraft or of persons or property on board the aircraft; or`
  line `( ii ) the good order and discipline on board the aircraft; or`
  line `( b ) that the person in question has done on the aircraft while in flight any act which in the opinion`
  line `of the commander is an offence under any law in force in the country in which the aircraft is`
  line `registered, not being a law of a political nature or based on racial or religious discrimination,`
  line `then, subject to the provisions of sub-section ( 4 ), the commander may take with respect to that person`
  line `such reasonable measures, including restraint of his person, as may be necessary —`
  line `( i ) to protect the safety of the aircraft or of persons or property on board the aircraft; or`
  line `( ii ) to maintain good order and discipline on board the aircraft; or`
  line `( iii ) to enable the commander to disembark or deliver that person in accordance with the`
  line `provisions of sub-section ( 5 ).`
  line `( 2 ) The aircraft commander may require the assistance of other crew members and may request, but`
  line `not require, the assistance of passengers or authorise other crew members and passengers, to restrain any`
  line `person whom he is entitled to restrain.`
  line `( 3 ) Any crew member or passenger may also take reasonable preventive measures without any`
  line `authorisation under sub-section ( 2 ) when he has reasonable grounds to believe that such action is`
  line `immediately necessary to protect the safety of the aircraft, or of persons or property therein.`
  line `( 4 ) Any restraint imposed on any person on board an aircraft under the powers conferred by the`
  line `foregoing provisions of this section shall not be continued after the time when the aircraft first thereafter`
  line `ceases to be in flight unless before or as soon as is reasonably practicable after that time, the commander`
  line `of the aircraft causes notification of the fact that a person on board the aircraft is under restraint and of the`
  line `reasons therefor to be sent to the appropriate authority of the country in which the aircraft so ceases to be`
  line `in flight, but subject to such notification may be continued after that time —`
  line `( a ) for any period (including the period of any further flight) between that time and the first`
  line `occasion thereafter on which the commander is able with any requisite consent of the appropriate`
  line `authorities to disembark or deliver the person under restraint in accordance with the provisions of`
  line `sub-section ( 5 ); or`
  line `( b ) if the person under restraint agrees to continue his journey under restraint on board that`
  line aircraft.
  line `( 5 ) The commander of an aircraft, —`
  line `( a ) if, in the case of any person on board the aircraft, he has reasonable grounds —`
  line `( i ) to believe as mentioned in clause ( a ) of sub-section ( 1 ); and`
obj_root_law_sections_4_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_5:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-5
  sectionNo (5)
  orderNo 5
  title `Page 5`
  content obj_root_law_sections_5_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_5_footnotes
  sourcePage 5
obj_root_law_sections_5_content:
  string
  line 5
  line `( ii ) to believe that it is necessary so to do in order to protect the safety of the aircraft or of`
  line `persons or property on board the aircraft or to maintain good order and discipline on board the`
  line aircraft,
  line `may disembark that person in any country in which that aircraft may be; and`
  line `( b ) if, in the case of any person on board the aircraft, he has reasonable grounds to believe as`
  line `mentioned in clause ( b ) of sub-section ( 1 ), may deliver that person to the appropriate authority.`
  line `( 6 ) The commander of an aircraft —`
  line `( a ) if he disembarks any person in pursuance of clause ( a ) of sub-section ( 5 ), in the case of an`
  line `Indian registered aircraft, in any country or, in the case of any other aircraft, in India, shall report the`
  line `fact of, and the reasons for, that disembarkation to —`
  line `( i ) the appropriate authority in the country of disembarkation; and`
  line `( ii ) the appropriate diplomatic or consular officer of the country of nationality of that person;`
  line `( b ) if he intends to deliver any person in pursuance of clause ( b ) of sub-section ( 5 ) in India, or in`
  line `the case of an Indian registered aircraft, in any other country which is a Convention country, shall`
  line `before or as soon as reasonably practicable after landing give notification of his intention and of the`
  line `reasons therefor —`
  line `( i ) to the appropriate authority; and`
  line `( ii ) in either case, to the appropriate diplomatic or consular officer of the country of`
  line `nationality of that person,`
  line `and any commander of an aircraft who without reasonable cause fails to comply with the requirements of`
  line `this sub-section shall be liable on summary conviction to a fine not exceeding one thousand rupees.`
  line `6. Jurisdiction. — ( 1 ) For the avoidance of doubt, it is hereby declared that for the purpose of any`
  line `proceedings before a court in India, any court having jurisdiction in respect of piracy committed on the`
  line `high seas shall have jurisdiction in respect of offences and other acts committed on board an aircraft as`
  line `d escribed in this Act wherever that offence o r act is committed.`
  line `( 2 ) For the purposes of conferring jurisdiction, an offence under any law in force in India, committed`
  line `on board an aircraft in flight shall be deemed to have been committed in any place in India where the`
  line `offender may for the time being be.`
  line `7. Provisions as to evidence in connection with aircraft. — ( 1 ) Where in any proceedings before a`
  line `court in India for an offence or other act committed on board an aircraft the testimony of any person is`
  line `requir ed and the court is satisfied that the person in question cannot be found in India, there shall be`
  line `admissible in evidence before that court any deposition relating to the subject matter of those proceedings`
  line `previously made on oath by that person outside In dia which was so made —`
  line `( a ) in the presence of the person charged with the offence; and`
  line `( b ) before a judge or a magistrate of a country such as is mentioned in the First Schedule to the`
  line `Citizenship Act, 1955 (57 of 1955) or before a consular officer of the Central Government.`
  line `( 2 ) Any such deposition shall be authenticated by the signature of the judge, magistrate or consular`
  line `officer before whom it was made and he shall certify that the person charged with the offence was present`
  line `at the taking of the deposition.`
  line `( 3 ) It shall not be necessary in any proceedings to prove the signature or official character of the`
  line `person appearing so to have authenticated any such deposition or to have given such a certificate, and`
  line `such a certificate shall, unless the contrary is proved, be sufficient evidence in any proceedings that the`
  line `person charged with the offence was p resent at the making of the deposition.`
  line `( 4 ) If a complaint is made to such a consular officer as aforesaid that any offence has been committed`
  line `on an Indian registered aircraft while in flight elsewhere than in or over India, that officer may enquire`
  line `into t he case upon oath.`
obj_root_law_sections_5_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_6:
  kind page
  sectionId pdf-page-6
  sectionNo (6)
  orderNo 6
  title `Page 6`
  content obj_root_law_sections_6_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_6_footnotes
  sourcePage 6
obj_root_law_sections_6_content:
  string
  line 6
  line `( 5 ) In this section —`
  line `( a ) the expression “ deposition ” includes an affidavit, affirmation or statement made upon`
  line `oath; and`
  line `( b ) the expression “ oath ” includes an affirmation or declaration in the case of persons allowed by`
  line `law to aff irm or declare instead of swearing,`
  line `and noting contained in this section shall prejudice the admission as evidence of any deposition which is`
  line `admissible in evidence apart from this section.`
  line `8. Provisions as to documentary evidence. — ( 1 ) In any legal proceedings under this Act, a`
  line `document published by the Ministry of the Central Government dealing with Civil Aviation and`
  line `purporting to be the publication known as “ Aeronautical Information Publication ” or a publication of the`
  line `series known as “ Notam ” and “ Aeronautical Information Circular ” shall be evidence of the matters`
  line `appearing from that document.`
  line `( 2 ) Any message or signal transmitted to or received from an aircraft which relates to the position of`
  line `the aircraft will be treated as evidence of certain records and shall apply to any legal proceedings.`
  line `CHAPTER IV`
  line `M ISCELLANEOUS`
  line `9. Power to apply the provisions of Act with modifications to certain aircraft. — The Central`
  line `Government may, by notification in the Official Gazette, direct that all or any of the provisions of this Act`
  line `shall apply to an aircraft referred to in sub - clause ( B ) of clause ( e ) of sub - section ( 1 ) of section 2, subject`
  line `to such modifications as may be specified in the notification.`
  line `10. Contracting parties to Convention. — The Central Government may, by notification in the`
  line `Official Gazette, certify as to who are the contracting parties to the Tokyo Convention and to what extent`
  line `they have availed themselves of the provisions of the Convention, and any such notification by the`
  line `Central Government shall be conclusive evidence of the matters certified therein.`
  line `11. Power to treat certain aircraft to be registered in Convention country. — If the Central`
  line `Go vernment is satisfied that the requirements of Article 18 of the Tokyo Convention have been satisfied`
  line `in relation to any aircraft, it may, by notification in the Official Gazette, direct that such aircraft shall, for`
  line `the purposes of this Act, be treated as registered in such Convention country as may be specified in the`
  line notification.
obj_root_law_sections_6_footnotes:
  string
  line
